\f0\fs30 My name is Halloween Jack, and it fits me. Only because I was born on one of those days where the sun and the earth perfectly aligned, and my mother cried out in fear at the dark light when I was born. She was never without a hint of that the rest of the time I knew her.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 My true Jack O Lantern nature- the wavery light behind the eyes, the wide grin that leaves open space- would be revealed that summer I was 15. The jack O lantern was named for the will o the wisp \'93foolish fires\'94 that would lead travelers astray as they made their way towards a home light that didn\'92t really exist.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I had a childhood, lived in her house and began to do civil war reenactments when I was 15, because Lotte Boule, her best friend... felt that I should have other interests besides helping her in and out of her wheelchair. Did I mention she was 400 lbs and ate only twinkies and bourbon. She was afraid of vegetables. You ask- what does all this have to do with Rex and the bayonet? I'm getting there- it all goes together
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 My mother\'92s name was Candelora Baker and she became pregnant with me after a late night spent working a forklift at the local printing plant. We live in a very small town, and the people here make do with what they can when they can. There isn't much to do, and my father was one more trucker who rolled through the night dragging eighteen wheels and metal box behind his pinup emblazoned mud flapped ass.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Momma never told me his name, and I suspect that she didn't ask for her own reasons. Back then she held herself high above the common herd, having been to a local community college and planning her escape from the confines of the longest mall strip in southern Kentucky.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 But the nights of too much studying took their toll, and in my mind I could see him, tall and possessing a full set of teeth and perhaps some swagger that men get when they walk into a place knowing that they can walk back out again.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 He saw a woman sitting on a plastic chair in the corner. Her hair had been tucked up earlier in the evening and her glasses were askew from having nodded off while watching the press do it\'92s infinite up and down. Her sleepy eyes widened and she stood, displaying a body that had none too many miles on it yet.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Words weren\'92t necessary for what happened next-they made quick, passionate love on a bale of packing peanuts . I came along 9 months later, putting paid to the career in data entry that my mother had wanted so badly.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I came downstairs on the summer of my 15
\fs18 \super th
\fs30 \nosupersub  year- the weak morning sunlight ate through the window like bile on the worn carpet. The front room had all the furniture out of it so Mam could move her rascal chair about. It was one of those automated ones that was a second- that meant that she could be going along happily when one wheel would spasm wildly twisting this way and that and making her progress in the world as herky jerky as you might think.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 And I knew- something about the way that mam shifted on her bed made it time to go and do the chores for her. They were exact and structured- she must be wiped down in concentric circles, the wheels of her chair oiled, the mind of her cat cleansed and a certain level of general hygiene to be attached to the rest of the house.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 \'93Hygiene, Jack, is the sign of a higher being. Dirty people do dirty things. \'93
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I would numbly nod, not really understanding but not wishing to appear stupid.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Lotte would talk to me about her sometimes, trying to explain in a way my small circled mind would understand.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 \'93If you as person knew about how many, many, MANY things happened to the woman who sits in that chair, you would not have that idea in your head about her no sir, you would not. There were so many sad endless nights for her - when you were a baby, she would rock you to sleep , not yet confined to the rolling prison of her own flesh.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 The house we lived in slanted to one side- it made pushing Mam round a tad more difficult .
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Lotte worked at the Jubitz as the general manager. Mam sometimes did their books, and that was how they became friends. Long nights watching the trucks come in and out of the huge parallel lines talking in desultory voices about the amount of fizz in the Dr. Pibb made them if not friends, at least people who knew something about each other. That was how things worked there, - people knew you - or they didn\'92t . It was something I could never properly get used to- that people knew of me and around me, but seemed to look right thru me on a daily basis.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Not used to it. But OK with it.
\f1\fs24 \

