\f0\fs30 The Eighth Texas Calvary had had it\'92s finest moment \'a0in Bardstown in 1862 . Nothing else of note had happened in Bardstown, with the exception of my birth in the intervening 210 years.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Since that was the amount of battles the fine men led by General John Wharton, I thought perhaps it was a sign, especially for me. In 1977, it seemed that I was destined to be part of the pageant; the parade I felt was always passing by just out of earshot, just out of reach.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I dreamed of being one of the soldiers, musket strapped \'a0to my back and the sound of the minie balls in \'a0air, whistling. It was the the thing I heard the most of when my daydreams led me far from Ms. Barton\'92s geometry class.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 As you passed the Quality Inn on the south side of town , near Delaney's Store on 31E on the way to Nazareth-you could hear the ghost feet sometimes. At least that is what I convinced myself of when I dressed myself in the replica \'a0clothes that Lotte Boule had made for me on her off time. In some ways she was more mother to me than my mother, actually paying attention to what I might need as a human being. She will always be my first love for that. The clothes were made of reworked carhartts and some pieces she had found in my Grampa\'92s attic.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Grampa \'a0\'a0died when I was 10. That sucked. He was a man of few words and even fewer ideas. I had gone into his bedroom and sat down next to him as he lay in bed. He was the only man who ever spent time in the house besides me. He had that scent of old that still can frighten me if I catch a whiff of it-it carried decay into my nostrils and up to my childish brain. It made a picture in my head of hospital beds and \'a0moss grown gravestones. He just looked at me for the longest moment ever- stretching it like toffee made of ashes. Then he was gone.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

