\f0\fs30 \cf0 The bayonet I carried was in less than perfect condition- it was obvious that it had had some parts broken off and that an unskilled hand had put it back together. It had a long thin barrel of some marled wood with a thin groove that ran along the top- that was the blood drain . The knife portion had been wired back on, one of the original screws missing . The wire was wrapped in some kind of rope that had been metalized, and it made the knife point off to the side instead of smoothly towards the enemy. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f0\fs30 \cf0  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  The piercing of the enemy at a short range- the need to look into the eyes of another being as you took it\'92s life- I wondered. Because life at that time didn\'92t seem to me to be a thing worth keeping, and I wondered if those who had it removed via that gun welcomed it as a chance to hand a gift to an enemy.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 But I did believe in being prepared, nonetheless. So I marched with a broomstick in the boots I got from Papa in the backyard, as many times as I could, back and forth, forth and back.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 So when I started the first, the very first battle of my career my hands and feet were callused already. I wanted to make a good impression on Rex- I knew that he was the holder of the weapons, holder of the grace. Keeper of all that meant so much to 15 year old me. I thought that if I could impress him with my marching there would be finally a moment and place where I fit in the world- a spot where it didn't feel too big or too small.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 A place where I was something other than the sum of being a mistake made by two lonely people, one disappearing and one staying here but imploding slowly, like a leaf off a tree.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I did not know that these thoughts were \'a0no more special or different from other people - I did know that it was my moment to shine. So I squared my shoulders and tucked the wooden gun over the thin bony right one . It\'92s twin was pulled back in a vain attempt to make my chest appear larger than it was. Sadly, this was not a strategy that worked, and the guy who stood next to me asked me if I was feeling OK.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 They talk about flashbulb memory, and I see these things from that day
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Flash: Lines of men, all in similarly itchy clothing, pulling flasks from their pockets and shifting from foot to foot. The lines they stood in were not in between any other lines.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Flash: The kentucky sunlight, flat, hard and unusually strong for that time of year. Late fall should have \'a0softened it like soaking bourbon mash, but for some reason did not.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Flash: Lotte Boule on the sideline, her kerchief hiding the fading blonde of her hair, but not the broad spread of her middle aged bosom. \'a0She was enamored of Rex, hence her desire for my participation. Rex owned the auto body shop on the outskirts of town, and was the closest you could come to an Eligible Bachelor in Bardstown. Lotte had dreams too, although she did not share them often.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Flash: Mam sitting next to her, tilted. It rent my heart that she could never seem to sit up straight, but this time was supposed to be my moment to make her proud. Also, even though the entire town knew who I was and how we lived- I had to pretend not to be known while I did this. It made me someone else.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Someone who could be worthy of the bayonet. I hoped that if I did a good enough job that Rex would let me keep it in my room at least. In preparation for this, I had pounded two pegs into the wall above my bed, hopefully the place where it would rest when not clutched in my bony hands.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Flash: the blue line of men on the other side of the field, their lines straighter than mine.Their faces looked shiny and fleshy with sweat. Somehow the color was darker in the sun- the hard light should have washed it out, but made it deeper.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I could see Gerard D\'92Amboux on the other side- he was in my Geometry class, and sometimes I stared at him, not sure what I was looking for. Was it me wanting to be him? Was it me being in love with him? At 15, I did not have words for all the feelings I had for a similar person. All I knew was that if he looked back I immediately pulled my face back in on itself, hoping not to be seen.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 But this was what Lotte had forced me out here for- to be seen, to touch someone other than Mam.
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 So we marched, and started to re- enact the battle, which mostly had consisted of General Wharton\'92s men , 66 of which had died during this battle , throwing themselves at the artillery with reckless abandon. While they had expired, they had also \'a0gained ground. That seemed to be the only \'a0correct measurements to me- the trading of a breath for some footage of ground. Never having been out of Bardstown made this arithmetic reasonable to me. So even though I really didn\'92t know what i was doing, I threw every ounce of my adolescent body into it, shouting a tenor war cry that harmonized well with the rest of teh baritones. the heat of the bodies around me, the stench of sweat, the knowledge that this was my moment all pulledt ogether until that moment- when I tripped. And fell. And took down 5 other re- enactors with me.....
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
