\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f0\fs30 \cf0 When I got up- the bayonet was broken. And it was stuck in me somehow . The haze of other people was around me- I didn\'92t know how or why it was all happening, just that i was both catylyst and stop sign in something that had never happened before.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f0\fs30 \cf0 The tangle of limbs and sweat and sharp edges was making me want to climb out of my skin- no place seemed up or down and \'a0the sounds of the men milling around us disoriented me even more. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f0\fs30 \cf0 When the smoke cleared , Cully Northland and Foster Williams both had parts of them entangled with parts of me. They were both from the other side of town, where nothing was held together by string. They stood, one long and lean and blonde and the other stocky and dark of face. I was in a prone position, my hands and knees scraped and the bayonet underneath my half turned body .
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f0\fs30 \cf0  The combination of embarassment and mortification were almost too much to bear, but I could hear Gramps voice in my ear- \'93 Get up you little fucker!- don\'92t let them see you down.....\'94 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f2\fs30 \cf0 The original battle was one where they were outnumbered 4 to one and they had succeeded by a strategic departure to Perryville. I wished more than anything to be in Perryville. It was about 5 miles distant. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f2\fs30 \cf0 But Mam and Lotte were \'a0right there- they would know of my shame. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f2\fs30 \cf0 I looked up and caught Mam\'92s eye. She looked worried, but proud. In some perverse way, I knew that was the only thing that I was really looking for, some place to let me shine in those eyes that were reflected by her spectacles. That one moment where I was not perfect- but still loved.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f2\fs30 \cf0 I picked myself up and dusted myself off. I picked up both of the pieces of the bayonet and marched my way through the rest of that sweaty, dry day. Everything hurt, but at least my shame was covered by the whoops and hollers of the other men around me. I even forgot myself so much as to whoop along with them 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f2\fs30 \cf0 After the re- enactment I sat down on the dry grass next to Mama and Lotte. The bayonet sat next to me, mournful in it\'92s destruction. They had set up a picnic on the patchwork quilt that Mam\'92s mam had made 20 years before. Lotte patted my hand and smiled. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340

\f2\fs30 \cf0 Rex came and sat down with us, eyeing the bowl of cold fried chicken as much as he was eying Lotte. His moustache was truly munificent, catching the last beams of the sun. At that moment I wished the quilt could cover me . I studied the pattern with a ferocity that should have burned holes in it. My face was red and felt as though it would peel off my skull. 
